@karimshebeika8010 The five mark coins were silver.  Hyperinflation only affects fiat currency, silver and gold doesn't suffer hyperinflation.  Whatever an ounce of silver will get you today is ROUGHLY comparable to what it will get you a year from now.  To put it into context, today, silver is up 21% for the year, but only up 0.5% over five years.  So it's beat inflation quite a bit this year, and has lost over inflation over five years, but on average, it's comparable.  Right now, however, the Venezuelan Bolivar lost 90% of its value in about 3-4 months, after losing 90% of its previous value in 3 months, after losing 90% of its previous value in 4 months, after losing 90% of its previous value in 6 months, etc. etc.


Add to that, in these circumstances, banks themselves aren't stable, and you can find a highly valuable life savings reduced to the value it would cost to buy a lunch, and then not even be able to withdraw it.  This was before countries had their own versions of the US"s FDIC.  That's why people in countries with distressed currencies with hyperinflation don't trust banks, often well past that era.  When you live with a hyperinflated currency, the cost of everything goes up, and people often have to be given leave from work several times a day to get basic necessities before the prices go up again.  Productivity is shot, consumer confidence is shot, and the value of work is shot.


That Venzuela example is a tame version of why his grandmother kept silver 5 Mark coins under her mattress.  Those retained their value, as silver was always actually worth something, unlike a wheelbarrow of hyperinflated currency.

